<TITLE> War crimes trial process has started: Sahara </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 14 (bdnews24.com) - The home minister has said she is personally happy over the arrest of two alleged war criminals in Rajshahi, which showed the process of trying 1971 war crimes had begun. "In line with our election pledge, the trial process of war criminals has started. They will all have to face trial in the homeland," said Sahara Khatun Saturday, speaking at the 14th founding anniversary of the Bangladesh Coast Guard.. Police arrested two Jamaat-e-Islami activistsDaud Hossain, 70, and Noor-e Anwar, 65from Mohanpur Upazila in Rajshahi Friday morning in a case that charged them with war crimes. Rajshahi police said it was the first instance in the country where alleged war criminals have been arrested in a regular case. An adviser to the prime minister said Saturday the government could make "a giant leap" in establishing rule of law in the country if the trial of war crimes were held properly. "Fair trial of all crimes carried out in the past is a must in establishing the rule of law," HT Imam told a roundtable at the National Press Club. Imam said it would be far more easier to try other killings if the trial of war criminals was held. "Now we've got an opportunity to try war criminals. Decisions are being taken and the relevant ministries will be directed to execute those decisions," he said bdnews
